DOZENS of people were quizzed in Glasgow as police returned to the scene of a brutal murder. Passers-by quizzed a week after murder DOZENS of people were quizzed in Glasgow as police returned to the scene of a brutal murder.Pedestrians and motorists were interviewed as part of a major operation to catch three thugs who stabbed a young dad to death.Stephen McGinlay, 26, was ambushed by a gang as he waited for his friend outside a chip shop last Thursday. One week on, detectives returned to the scene in St George's Road, in Woodside.Today they are sifting through information provided by members of the public during the hour-long operation.Police revealed they were hunting three men over the murder of Stephen, from Possilpark, who died in hospital four days after the attack.A dark car was a key line of inquiry for officers in yesterday's operation.As revealed by the Evening Times, senior officers believe the vehicle is the &quot;forensic link&quot; between Stephen and the killers.It was spotted heading along the busy road after the stabbing at around 5.50pm.Stephen was left covered in blood, staggering along the road, as the gang fled. He went into chip shop, Prego, where his friend was, to ask for help and it's believed he asked staff for a glass of water before collapsing.Detective Chief Inspector Bob Frew, who is leading the inquiry, said: &quot;Some members of the public may have seen the incident and not realised the severity of the situation.&quot;Police believe the attack was &quot;targeted&quot; and Stephen may have known his attackers.Stephen's killers arrived and left in the dark car. A police insider said: &quot;There's a good chance these guys had blood on them when they jumped back in the car. It's is our forensic link between the killers and the victim. It's vital we find it.&quot;Anyone with information should contact Govan police on 101.rebecca.gray@eveningtimes.co.uk 